Angular has always focused on making dependency injection simpler, more predictable, and easier to maintain.
With the upcoming Angular v22.1 minor release, developers will get a new migration schematic that helps convert existing @Injectable() services into the newer @Service() syntax automatically.
Instead of manually updating every service file, Angular CLI will handle the migration while keeping your existing behavior intact.
The Evolution from @Injectable() to @Service()
For years, Angular services have been created using the @Injectable() decorator.
A typical service looks like this:
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';@Injectable({
providedIn: 'root'
})
export class ProductRepository {
getProducts() {
return [];
}
}
This approach works perfectly, but Angular v22 introduces a more focused decorator:
import { Service } from '@angular/core';@Service()
export class ProductRepository {
getProducts() {
return [];
}
}
